{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9892,"record_hash":"sha256:a2a4db8ba6a2b7a876ce05c2e5b428c72279502b3af975a8653d6508afcf083c","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:35:55.565Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: /Users/kiril/Documents/tars/Tars/02 [REDACTED:entropy].md\n@@\n ## Design Bias\n \n The agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n@@\n Do not bake a model-generated summary into storage. If a summary exists later,\n make it a derived convenience artifact, not the source of truth.\n+\n+## Prior Art Notes\n+\n+Research as of 2026-05-20 points to a few strong patterns.\n+\n+### Native Session Resume\n+\n+[Claude Code sessions](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/sessions) and\n+[GitHub Copilot CLI session data](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-cli/use-copilot-cli/chronicle)\n+both expose direct resume flows:\n+\n+- continue the most recent session\n+- open a session picker\n+- resume by session id or name\n+- rename sessions\n+- export or share a transcript\n+\n+Claude also exposes branch/worktree filtering in the picker and lets users fork\n+a session. Copilot CLI stores raw session files plus a derived local session\n+store, then uses that store for `/chronicle` reports, history questions, and\n+instruction-improvement suggestions.\n+\n+The lesson for GitButler is not to mimic native resume. Native resume only works\n+inside one provider's session model. GitButler's stronger role is portable\n+reference: help a different machine or agent discover, inspect, and selectively\n+load prior work.\n+\n+### Checkpoints And Durable State\n+\n+[LangGraph persistence](https://langchain-5e9cc07a.mintlify.app/oss/python/langgraph/persistence)\n+and\n+[Copilot SDK session persistence](https://docs.github.com/en/enterprise-cloud@latest/copilot/how-tos/copilot-sdk/use-copilot-sdk/session-persistence)\n+separate a stable thread/session id from resumable checkpoints or state.\n+Copilot SDK also calls out that meaningful session ids matter and that resumed\n+sessions may change model, working directory, tools, or skill configuration.\n+\n+The lesson is to keep agentlog turns as durable checkpoints of observed work,\n+and to avoid assuming the receiving agent has the same runtime, tools, model, or\n+provider.\n+\n+### Resources, Tools, And Prompts\n+\n+[MCP server concepts](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/learn/server-concepts)\n+draws a useful line:\n+\n+- tools are model-invoked operations\n+- resources are discoverable context\n+- prompts are reusable user-controlled workflows\n+\n+That maps well to handoff:\n+\n+- `sessions` and `timeline` are context resources\n+- `related-detail` is a read tool\n+- a future skill or prompt can teach the catch-up workflow\n+\n+The lesson is to make the data browseable and bounded, not to force everything\n+through one command that returns a wall of text.\n+\n+### Context Providers And Repo Maps\n+\n+[Continue context providers](https://docs.continue.dev/customize/custom-providers)\n+and [Aider's repository map](https://aider.chat/docs/repomap.html) both show the\n+same pattern: give the model compact orientation first, then let it ask for more\n+specific context. Aider's map is especially relevant because it is not the full\n+repo; it is a token-budgeted outline that guides later reads.\n+\n+The lesson is that a handoff command should start with an outline card:\n+sessions, turns, counts, agents, recency, branch/review/change hits, and small\n+previews. Full transcript hydration should be a second step.\n+\n+### Review And Provenance Workflows\n+\n+Developer platforms treat provenance as a lightweight ledger, not just a blob of\n+chat. Useful references:\n+\n+- [GitHub pull request reviews](https://docs.github.[REDACTED:entropy])\n+- [GitLab system notes](https://docs.gitlab.com/user/project/system_notes/)\n+- [Gerrit Change-Ids](https://gerrit-review.googlesource.com/Documentation/user-changeid.html)\n+- [git trailers](https://git-scm.com/docs/git-interpret-trailers.html)\n+\n+The lesson is to use stable ids and structured links. Handoff should preserve\n+the relationship between branch, review, change, session, and turn evidence, but\n+avoid heavyweight supply-chain attestation machinery in v1.\n+\n+## Research Takeaways\n+\n+The handoff feature should copy these ideas:\n+\n+- branch/worktree-aware discovery\n+- named or previewable sessions when we have names/previews\n+- resume/fork/reference as separate concepts\n+- compact outlines before full transcript reads\n+- derived summaries as conveniences, not truth\n+- stable ids and links across rebases or branch movement\n+- reindexable derived stores if we add local acceleration later\n+\n+It should not copy these:\n+\n+- provider-native resume semantics for cross-provider handoff\n+- automatic ingestion of all related transcript records\n+- persistent generated summaries as the only source of truth\n+- cryptographic provenance or SLSA-style ceremony for v1\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:35:55.565Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}